Educational Service District 105
July 20 at 8:09 AM ·

Applications are open through August 16 to become part of the Yakima Herald-Republic's 2020-21 "Unleashed" student journalism team! Prospective members must be an incoming 9th-12th grader who is attending an ESD 105 region school that is participating in the 2020-21 Unleashed program, must commit to attending twice-a-month group planning meetings online (and eventually in person), must commit to producing at least 10 publishable items during the year ... and must enjoy the opportunity to share -- and expand -- their existing stellar creative talents with the thousands of readers of the YHR!

The newspaper's monthly Unleashed section is provided through a partnership involving ESD 105 and schools from our area. You can find the application here at the newspaper's website:
https://www.yakimaherald.com/site/forms/unleashed/

Pandemic EBT will be available soon in WA. P-EBT is a new emergency program for ALL children in grades K-12, who receive free or reduced-price school meals. P-EBT provides families with funds to pay the cost of meals while schools are closed due to COVID-19.

If you receive Basic Food through DSHS AND receive free or reduced-price school meals - no application is required. You will automatically receive these benefits on your EBT cart.
If you receive TANF, Foster, Migrant, Homeless, or Medicaid - you MUST apply for P-EBT.
If your child receives free or reduced-price meals AND do not receive Basic Food - you MUST apply for P-EBT.

ONLY CONTACT CHILD NUTRITION (509-972-6044) IF YOU DO NOT RECEIVE FREE OR REDUCED-PRICE MEALS AND MAY BE ELIGIBLE. TO APPLY FOR P-EBT, PLEASE VISIT WASHINGTONCONNECTION.ORG OR BY CALLING 877-501-2233. APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED BY AUGUST 31, 2020.

Valerie and Katelyn Longgland brought a smile to their neighbors faces when they placed flowers on their doorstep, rang the doorbell and ran. It’s a tradition they do every year on May 1st. Friends are always surprised by the spring blossom waiting for them. This year was even more meaningful. During this global pandemic people are finding safe ways to stay connected and lift each other’s spirits. Valerie and Katelyn were happy to hear from many neighbors how this simple gesture brightened their day. What a sweet “win” for Valerie, Katelyn and their neighbors!

https://wvsdyakima.blogspot.com/

The Association of Washington School Principals is seeking nominations for its PRINCIPAL OF THE YEAR award and its ASSISTANT PRINCIPAL OF THE YEAR award. This year, AWSP will be making an ESD-wide regional recognition in each of those two categories, with the regional honorees then vying for their category's statewide award. Anyone can nominate a principal or an assistant principal from your school district. Deadline to nominate an assistant principal is March 2, and deadline to nominate a school principal is March 13. Details are here at the AWSP's website: http://www.awsp.org/inside-awsp/awards/principal-of-the-year

We are excited to welcome aboard CBRE Heery as our project management team. Rob Gross will serve as the senior project manager. Rob has over 19 years of experience and will be the District’s day to day contact. David Beaudine will serve as our managing director. David has over 16 years of experience and will oversee the project launch and development. Roxann Robinson will oversee program controls and administration. Roxann has over 16 years of experience and will be responsible for documentation and cost control. We are looking forward to great work ahead!

Jon Gores, managing director for D A Davidson, presented the financial plan and schedule for the sale of bonds during the school board meeting held April 8, 2019. The West Valley School board approved the sale of the bonds.
Educational Specifications were underway today. This is the programing phase of school construction. Architects met with West Valley staff to gather information on how the the building spaces need to function. The goal is to understand the needs of the district and prepare a narrative of these needs to be reviewed and edited. The next phase of the project will include preliminary drawings! wvbuildingourfuture.org

West Valley High School, Yakima
February 10, 2019 at 7:35 PM ·

Drum roll please...
This event is ON FOR TODAY! Our amazing custodians are working on the parking lot and sidewalks. Our DECA students are so excited to host and help you have a great time.

We realize this new day and time won’t work for everyone. We also realize some of you will choose to stay off the roads. We are really sorry this year didn’t work out differently.

When I can talk to the right people and make sure I have the correct info and forms I will post about how you can get a refund if you’ve purchased tickets you won’t be able to use.

This is a fundraising event for DECA and helps our students with the expenses of their state and national competitions. They will be happy with any amount they can raise and if they have to be creative because this year’s attendance is really down - that will be a real world, real life lesson we can work through.

Thanks for sticking with us and for your patience this morning. It was nice to not have my phone blow up with notifications!

post_text:
WVMS 6th grade band was one of nine bands from six different states (Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Montana, Wyoming, and Alaska) selected to perform at the National Music Education Association’s All-Northwest Conference on Saturday, February 16 in Portland, Oregon at the Portland Convention Center. This is the first time that a band from West Valley has been selected to perform at a conference of this magnitude!
The band will be performing once at the clinic, where instructor Maegan Ley will be presenting and again during the afternoon concert hour. The opening song, of their six songs, will be the world debut of a new piece by Brian Balmages called “Thunderbolt Fanfare”. . . .Brian has been one of the greatest composers of band literature for the past 15 years, and his music is played by middle school, high school, and college bands all over world . . . . WVMS 6th grade band was able to commission him to write a piece to perform at the conference (thanks to generous donations and a grant from the West Valley Schools Foundation).

post_text: Three outstanding candidates came forward to represent the West Valley community for the position of School Board Director District #4. The School Board was very impressed with the quality of all candidates who applied. Following last week’s interviews, the Board spent a great deal of time reflecting and weighing the qualifications of each applicant. After an Executive Session at the School Board meeting on October 8, the Board invited Dr. Barbara Gilbert to serve as School Board Director District #4 for the West Valley School District. Dr. Gilbert has a Doctoral Degree in Educational Leadership from Seattle University and is active in the community with YWCA, Cowiche Canyon Conservancy and other community organizations. We are grateful for Dr. Gilbert’s willingness to serve the West Valley community in this capacity. Thank you to all who applied.

April 29, 2016 at 4:54 PM ·

West Valley School District #208 Parents/Guardians – As we continue to move forward toward implementation of our ENGAGE – Blended Learning Initiative for the start of the 2016-17 school year, we are trying to provide every resource possible in order to best implement our vision for the best possible learning environment for our students. Part of this is to do all that we can to provide a safe learning environment for our students.

The Superintendent Advisory Council Meeting on May 17th at 6:30 p.m. West Valley Junior High School Library will provide parents with valuable information on Internet Safety.

Detective Mike Durbin from the Yakima Police Special Assault Unit will be presenting on Tuesday, May 17, 2016 at 6:30 p.m. He will presenting to parents about Internet Dangers.

This will be a 20 minute presentation with question and answer time to follow. Remember that a light dinner is available as well. Hope to see you all there!

West Valley PreK Workshop that is scheduled for Thursday, Aug. 20, 6:30 pm – 8:00 pm, at Wide Hollow Elementary.

Wide Hollow is located at 1000 S. 72nd Ave, Yakima, WA 98908.

The focus of the workshop will be: Early Identification of Disabilities.

“Learn the developmental milestones in reading, writing, math, fine motor skills, gross motor skills, and speech. Learn how to address concerns by working with your local Director of Special Services.”

The workshop will be led by Lucas Jaeger, Director of Special Services for the West Valley School District.

This free workshop is open to all early learning providers and parents/guardians in our region who would like to learn about this topic.

“Learn the developmental milestones in reading, writing, math, fine motor skills, gross motor skills, and speech. Learn how to address concerns by working with your local Director of Special Services.”

The workshop will be led by Lucas Jaeger, Director of Special Services for the West Valley School District.

This free workshop is open to all early learning providers and parents/guardians in our region who would like to learn about this topic.

I wish it would have been just another Tuesday on the countdown to summer. But today wasn't an ordinary Tuesday. While the sadness and great injustice of Zhane's loss was present all day, so were many acts comfort, care and concern. I was really proud to be a RAM today and so impressed by how our kids took care of each other and their broken hearts. For example, 4 students making this memorial space for his friends to honor him just because "we want to do something for them - how can we help them?"

post_text:
Refinancing Bond Debt - $4 Million over Past Three Years

What does this mean for you?

We have shared our efforts toward fiscal responsibility over the past three years in refinancing bond debt to save just over $4 million dollars. We will continue to follow this trend of researching these opportunities in the years ahead as well. You might ask yourself – Where will I see the impact of this refinancing effort? You will see this on your tax statements from the county in the years ahead as we continue to refinance debt and the overall growth in housing in the area further divides the tax burden among more people.
